The Thomas R. Carper Water Resources Development Act (WRDA) of 2024 passed both Chambers and is headed to @POTUS to be signed into law. Here are key provisions @SenBrianSchatz and I secured for Hawaii:

1⃣ Maui Wildfire Response:
- Prioritize Maui watershed assessments in recommending construction or modification of water resources development projects.
- Create a new project to conduct a feasibility study for flood risk management and ecosystem restoration in the County of Maui.
- Carry out a post-disaster watershed assessment for areas impacted by the August 2023 wildfires on Maui.

2⃣Expand Access to Resources:
- Allow U.S. Army Corps of Engineers to partner with stakeholders on a broader range of projects including cultural resources preservation and environmental restoration.
- Expand remote and subsistence harbors eligibility.
- Create an avenue for remote, coastal areas to include comprehensive cultural, social, and ecosystem benefits in cost-benefit analyses for small hurricane and storm damage reduction projects.

3⃣Strengthen Disaster Resilience:
- Expand scope to consider disaster resilience and enhanced national security from utilization of the Honolulu harbor by the Department of Defense.
- Expedite the completion of the repairs of the damaged seawall at Laupahoehoe Harbor.
- Modify the current Hanapepe Levee project to evaluate sources of flooding and propose engineering and non-structural solutions to reduce flood damages in the Hanapepe River watershed.
- Modify the current Waimea project to evaluate sources of flooding in the Waimea River watershed and investigate modifications to existing Waimea River levees on the southwest coast of Kauai.
- Authorize a new project to conduct a feasibility study for flood risk management in Hawaii Kai.

Great news—@FEMA just announced it will be extending housing assistance to Maui wildfire survivors for an additional year.

The extension of the Individuals and Households Program (IHP), including Financial Assistance and Direct Temporary Housing Assistance was originally set to end on February 10, 2025, but will now be extended to February 10, 2026.

There are currently 1,194 households occupying FEMA-provided units, and with this extension, survivors housed in temporary FEMA units will be able to continue working on their permanent housing plan and start paying rent, depending on their financial ability.

Occupants who provide documentation of their post-disaster income that meets or is below HUD’s very low-income limit will qualify for fully reduced rent of $50 per month without having to appeal and submit documentation of pre- or post-disaster housing costs.

Occupants with household incomes above the HUD very low-income limit will only have to provide documentation of post-disaster housing costs for FEMA to evaluate the amount of rent to be charged based on their financial ability.

FEMA will conduct outreach to assist occupants of temporary housing units with the documentation necessary to evaluate their ability to pay.

For more information on temporary housing, call the Individual Assistance Housing Hotline at 808-784-1600, contact 2-1-1 to reach the disaster case management program, or call FEMA Helpline at 800-621-3362 for assistance in other languages. You can also get help in-person at Lahaina Gateway  (next to Ace Hardware) or the CNHA Office next to Maui Mall in Kahului.
